  "quizBackupQ4": "What are versioned backups and why are they important?",
  "@quizBackupQ4": {
    "description": "quizBackupQ4"
  },
  "quizBackupQ4A1": "Storing multiple file copies from different dates - allows rolling back to a needed version",
  "@quizBackupQ4A1": {
    "description": "quizBackupQ4A1"
  },
  "quizBackupQ4A2": "Creating a backup every day in the same folder",
  "@quizBackupQ4A2": {
    "description": "quizBackupQ4A2"
  },
  "quizBackupQ4A3": "Using different passwords for each backup",
  "@quizBackupQ4A3": {
    "description": "quizBackupQ4A3"
  },
  "quizBackupQ4A4": "Copying files from different computers to one drive",
  "@quizBackupQ4A4": {
    "description": "quizBackupQ4A4"
  },
  "quizBackupQ4Explain": "Versioned backups store change history. If a file was corrupted a week ago but you noticed only today - you can restore an older version. Without versions, you'd overwrite good data with damaged data.",
  "@quizBackupQ4Explain": {
    "description": "quizBackupQ4Explain"
  },
  "quizBackupQ5": "Why are backups critical during a ransomware attack?",
  "@quizBackupQ5": {
    "description": "quizBackupQ5"
  },
  "quizBackupQ5A1": "They let you restore data without paying the ransom",
  "@quizBackupQ5A1": {
    "description": "quizBackupQ5A1"
  },
  "quizBackupQ5A2": "Ransomware can't infect backups",
  "@quizBackupQ5A2": {
    "description": "quizBackupQ5A2"
  },
  "quizBackupQ5A3": "Backups automatically remove the virus",
  "@quizBackupQ5A3": {
    "description": "quizBackupQ5A3"
  },
  "quizBackupQ5A4": "Police use backups to find hackers",
  "@quizBackupQ5A4": {
    "description": "quizBackupQ5A4"
  },
  "quizBackupQ5Explain": "Ransomware encrypts your files and demands payment. If you have an offline backup (disconnected from the network), you simply restore your data. Important: a backup on a connected drive can also be encrypted!",
  "@quizBackupQ5Explain": {
    "description": "quizBackupQ5Explain"
  },
  "quizDownloadQ4": "Why is it dangerous to download from aggregator sites (Softonic, CNET Downloads)?",
  "@quizDownloadQ4": {
    "description": "quizDownloadQ4"
  },
  "quizDownloadQ4A1": "They often bundle installers with adware and potentially unwanted programs",
  "@quizDownloadQ4A1": {
    "description": "quizDownloadQ4A1"
  },
  "quizDownloadQ4A2": "Programs on aggregators always contain viruses",
  "@quizDownloadQ4A2": {
    "description": "quizDownloadQ4A2"
  },
  "quizDownloadQ4A3": "They slow down download speed",
  "@quizDownloadQ4A3": {
    "description": "quizDownloadQ4A3"
  },
  "quizDownloadQ4A4": "Aggregators are not available in all countries",
  "@quizDownloadQ4A4": {
    "description": "quizDownloadQ4A4"
  },
  "quizDownloadQ4Explain": "Aggregators (Softonic, Download.com) often wrap the original installer in their own downloader with adware, toolbars, and potentially unwanted programs. Download directly from the developer's website.",
  "@quizDownloadQ4Explain": {
    "description": "quizDownloadQ4Explain"
  },
  "quizDownloadQ5": "How do attackers disguise malicious files?",
  "@quizDownloadQ5": {
    "description": "quizDownloadQ5"
  },
  "quizDownloadQ5A1": "Using double extensions: document.pdf.exe appears as PDF",
  "@quizDownloadQ5A1": {
    "description": "quizDownloadQ5A1"
  },
  "quizDownloadQ5A2": "Drawing an antivirus icon on it",
  "@quizDownloadQ5A2": {
    "description": "quizDownloadQ5A2"
  },
  "quizDownloadQ5A3": "Renaming the file to 'antivirus'",
  "@quizDownloadQ5A3": {
    "description": "quizDownloadQ5A3"
  },
  "quizDownloadQ5A4": "They don't - users download viruses themselves",
  "@quizDownloadQ5A4": {
    "description": "quizDownloadQ5A4"
  },
  "quizDownloadQ5Explain": "Windows hides known extensions by default. A file 'report.pdf.exe' displays as 'report.pdf' with a PDF icon. Enable extension display: Explorer → View → File name extensions.",
  "@quizDownloadQ5Explain": {
    "description": "quizDownloadQ5Explain"
  },
  "quiz2faQ4": "Why is an authenticator app better than SMS for 2FA?",
  "@quiz2faQ4": {
    "description": "quiz2faQ4"
  },
  "quiz2faQ4A1": "SMS can be intercepted via SIM-swap attacks or SS7 vulnerabilities",
  "@quiz2faQ4A1": {
    "description": "quiz2faQ4A1"
  },
  "quiz2faQ4A2": "The app works offline",
  "@quiz2faQ4A2": {
    "description": "quiz2faQ4A2"
  },
  "quiz2faQ4A3": "SMS costs money",
  "@quiz2faQ4A3": {
    "description": "quiz2faQ4A3"
  },
  "quiz2faQ4A4": "The app looks better",
  "@quiz2faQ4A4": {
    "description": "quiz2faQ4A4"
  },
  "quiz2faQ4Explain": "SIM-swap: an attacker transfers your number to their SIM card through the carrier. SS7: a telephony protocol vulnerability allows SMS interception. An authenticator (TOTP) generates codes locally on the device.",
  "@quiz2faQ4Explain": {
    "description": "quiz2faQ4Explain"
  },
  "quiz2faQ5": "What is TOTP and how does it work?",
  "@quiz2faQ5": {
    "description": "quiz2faQ5"
  },
  "quiz2faQ5A1": "A one-time code generated every 30 seconds based on a secret key and current time",
  "@quiz2faQ5A1": {
    "description": "quiz2faQ5A1"
  },
  "quiz2faQ5A2": "A permanent password sent by the server",
  "@quiz2faQ5A2": {
    "description": "quiz2faQ5A2"
  },
  "quiz2faQ5A3": "Encryption of communication between two devices",
  "@quiz2faQ5A3": {
    "description": "quiz2faQ5A3"
  },
  "quiz2faQ5A4": "Phone unlock technology using fingerprint",
  "@quiz2faQ5A4": {
    "description": "quiz2faQ5A4"
  },
  "quiz2faQ5Explain": "TOTP (Time-based One-Time Password) uses a shared secret key and current time to generate a 6-digit code. The code changes every 30 seconds and works only once - intercepting it is useless.",
  "@quiz2faQ5Explain": {
    "description": "quiz2faQ5Explain"
  },
  "quizUsbQ4": "What is a USB Rubber Ducky attack?",
  "@quizUsbQ4": {
    "description": "quizUsbQ4"
  },
  "quizUsbQ4A1": "A device disguised as a keyboard that instantly types malicious commands",
  "@quizUsbQ4A1": {
    "description": "quizUsbQ4A1"
  },
  "quizUsbQ4A2": "A virus that wipes flash drive data",
  "@quizUsbQ4A2": {
    "description": "quizUsbQ4A2"
  },
  "quizUsbQ4A3": "A flash drive with extremely large storage",
  "@quizUsbQ4A3": {
    "description": "quizUsbQ4A3"
  },
  "quizUsbQ4A4": "A USB device for hacking Wi-Fi",
  "@quizUsbQ4A4": {
    "description": "quizUsbQ4A4"
  },
  "quizUsbQ4Explain": "USB Rubber Ducky looks like a regular flash drive, but the computer sees it as a keyboard. In seconds, it 'types' a script: opens terminal, downloads malware, disables protection - faster than you can notice.",
  "@quizUsbQ4Explain": {
    "description": "quizUsbQ4Explain"
  },
  "quizUsbQ5": "How can you safely check the contents of an unknown flash drive?",
  "@quizUsbQ5": {
    "description": "quizUsbQ5"
  },
  "quizUsbQ5A1": "Use an isolated virtual machine or a computer without network access",
  "@quizUsbQ5A1": {
    "description": "quizUsbQ5A1"
  },
  "quizUsbQ5A2": "Insert and quickly look - the virus won't have time to infect",
  "@quizUsbQ5A2": {
    "description": "quizUsbQ5A2"
  },
  "quizUsbQ5A3": "Format the drive before use",
  "@quizUsbQ5A3": {
    "description": "quizUsbQ5A3"
  },
  "quizUsbQ5A4": "Ask a friend to check on their computer",
  "@quizUsbQ5A4": {
    "description": "quizUsbQ5A4"
  },
  "quizUsbQ5Explain": "The safe way is a virtual machine (VirtualBox, Hyper-V) without network access. Even if the drive is infected, the virus stays inside the virtual environment and won't harm the main system.",
  "@quizUsbQ5Explain": {
    "description": "quizUsbQ5Explain"
  },
